05959nam a22010095i 9780674293380DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1374428089  a97806742933807 a10.4159/97806742933802doi  a(DE-B1597)642332  a(OCoLC)1373987627  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aPOL0610002bisacsh04a364.15/1qOCoLC223/eng/202211231 aPort, Andrew I., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNever Again :bGermans and Genocide after the Holocaust /cAndrew I. Port. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (416 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPrologue -- tIntroduction: The Consummate Country of Contrition -- tCOLD WAR GENOCIDE: CARNAGE IN CAMBODIA -- tGENOCIDE AFTER GERMAN UNIFICATION: CRIMES AGAINST HUMANITY IN BOSNIA AND RWANDA -- tConclusion: Acting after Auschwitz -- tEpilogue -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tArchival Sources and Interviews -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGermans remember the Nazi past so that it may never happen again. But how has the abstract vow to remember translated into concrete action to prevent new genocides abroad?As reports of mass killings in Bosnia spread in the middle of 1995, Germans faced a dilemma. Should the Federal Republic deploy its military to the Balkans to prevent a genocide, or would departing from postwar Germany’s pacifist tradition open the door to renewed militarism? In short, when Germans said “never again,” did they mean “never again Auschwitz” or “never again war”?Looking beyond solemn statements and well-meant monuments, Andrew I. Port examines how the Nazi past shaped German responses to the genocides in Cambodia, Bosnia, and Rwanda—and further, how these foreign atrocities recast Germans’ understanding of their own horrific history. In the late 1970s, the reign of the Khmer Rouge received relatively little attention from a firmly antiwar public that was just “discovering” the Holocaust. By the 1990s, the genocide of the Jews was squarely at the center of German identity, a tectonic shift that inspired greater involvement in Bosnia and, to a lesser extent, Rwanda. Germany’s increased willingness to use force in defense of others reflected the enthusiastic embrace of human rights by public officials and ordinary citizens. At the same time, conservatives welcomed the opportunity for a more active international role involving military might—to the chagrin of pacifists and progressives at home.Making the lessons, limits, and liabilities of politics driven by memories of a troubled history harrowingly clear, Never Again is a story with deep resonance for any country confronting a dark past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBosnien and Herzegovina. 0aGenocidezGermanyxPublic opinion. 0aGermansxAttitudes. 0aImperialismus. 0aJudenvernichtung. 0aKambodscha. 0aKollektives Gedächtnis. 0aKolonialismus. 0aKriegsverbrechen. 0aMenschenrechte. 0aRwandan Genocide, Rwanda, 1994. 0aSrebrenica. 0aVölkermord. 0aYugoslav War, 1991-1995xAtrocitieszBosnia and Herzegovina. 4aHUP. 4aHarvard University Press. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Genocide & War Crimes.2bisacsh  aCold War.  aFinal Solution.  aKlaus Kinkel.  aNational Socialism.  aPol Pot.  aRaphael Lemkin.  aSrebrenica.  aThird Reich.  aVergangenheitsbewaltigung.  aethnic cleansing.  ahumanitarian aid.  aintervention.  amedia coverage.  apolicy.  arape.  arefugees.  aviolence.  axenophobia.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is par